title: Comparing apples to error theory: Alternative antirealist metaethical positions
description:
Some philosophers maintain that there are only three antirealist positions:

(1) Relativism
(2) Error theory
(3) Noncognitivism

This is not true. There are at least three additional positions available to moral antirealism. All three positions depict one's account of the semantics of folk metaethical discourse as uniform (all moral judgments mean the same thing) and determinate (all moral judgments do or do not express propositions, are or are not referring to objective moral properties, and so on). See Gill (2009) for a discussion of this topic.

However, it is possible that philosophers are simply mistaken about the uniformity and determinacy of folk discourse. There are at least two available positions in addition to standard uniform and determinate accounts with respect to folk metaethics:

(a) Metaethical variability/pluralism
(b) Metaethical indeterminacy

One can appeal to (a) and (b) to argue for at least three alternative positions to (1), (2), and (3). These are:

(i) Hybrid accounts: you can endorse relativism about some discourse, error theory about some, and noncognitive about some (or some combination of these).


(ii) Incoherentism

People may be committed to conflicting positions, which introduces a new form of antirealism according to which moral claims are incoherent.


(iii) Quietism & the unintelligibility thesis

It could be that questions about moral realism and antirealism don‚Äôt figure into ordinary thought and language. Instead, the relevant sorts of distinctions and concepts may be exclusive to academic philosophy. They may also be the result of conceptual and linguistic confusions that don‚Äôt impinge on ordinary thought. If so, the dispute between realists and antirealists may have little or nothing to do with folk metaethics; it might even be the case that there simply is no folk metaethics of the relevant kind. If so, we can reject moral realism on the grounds that it isn‚Äôt even intelligible.

Third third view is my view: I do not think there are determinate folk metaethical positions for the most part, and I think philosophical accounts of realism are a product of metaphilosophical errors characteristic of doing philosophy. I discuss these alternative positions in this video.

References

Gill, M. B. (2009). Indeterminacy and variability in meta-ethics. Philosophical studies, 145, 215-234.

title: Are most people moral realists?
description:
‚ÄúThe central task to which contemporary moral philosophers have addressed themselves is that of listing the distinctive characteristics of moral utterances.‚Äù - Alasdair MacIntyre (1957)

---

Moral philosophers often claim that most ordinary people are moral realists, or they will claim that most people find moral realism intuitive.

Over the past twenty years, growing empirical evidence casts doubt on this claim. While the findings are not decisive, researchers consistently find large numbers of participants favor antirealist positions.

However, should we accept these results at face value? I don't think so. I am skeptical of these results. Yet skepticism about these findings does not, I believe, favor the conclusion that most people are moral realists after all. Instead, it favors a radical rethinking of the relationship between ordinary thought and philosophy.

title: Normative entanglement: The conflation of metaethics and normative ethics
description:
Normative entanglement occurs whenever statements or questions conflate metaethical and normative considerations in such a way that one's statements about, or responses to what are ostensibly intended to be questions about metaethics could be plausibly interpreted to have pragmatic implications about one's normative stance or one's personality, character, or attitudes. 

For instance, if someone denies that "murder is objectively wrong," this could be interpreted to imply that the person does not think murder is morally wrong, or that they think it is less wrong than someone who would agree with this statement. In addition, such a person may be perceived as less opposed to murder, less upset by murder, less willing to prevent it, more likely to engage in it, and so on.

I suspect normative entanglement plays an important and so far underappreciated role in bolstering the appeal of moral realism. I discuss why in this video. For the original blog post about this topic, see here:

https://www.lanceindependent.com/post/normative-entanglement-a-new-name-for-an-old-rhetorical-trick

title: What is metaethical pluralism?
description:
If you support what I am doing at this channel, please subscribe and like the video.

---

I will be discussing another topic from my blog, metaethical pluralism. You can find the original post here:

https://www.lanceindependent.com/post/what-is-metaethical-pluralism

Metaethical pluralism is the view that there isn't a single uniform and determinate analysis of moral judgment and discourse. Instead, there are ineliminable elements of two or more metaethical positions. 

For instance, it may be that some people use moral claims to express nonpropositional attitudes (such as emotions or imperatives), while others use moral claims to express propositional claims. If so, this would suggest that some moral language is used in a way more consistent with noncognitivism, while other moral language is used in a way more consistent with cognitivism.

I encountered the notion of metaethical pluralism in Michael Gill's work on metaethical indeterminacy and variability. See this paper:

Gill, M. B. (2009). Indeterminacy and variability in meta-ethics. Philosophical studies, 145, 215-234.

There, Gill describes metaethical "variability." In the ensuing years, empirical evidence has provided increasing support for the notion that ordinary people don't consistently use moral terms in a way that comports with one or another competing analyses of the metaethical presuppositions implicit in the way they think and speak. This supports Gill's suggestion that an accurate descriptive account of ordinary moral language may exhibit ineliminable metaethical variability. Much of this research began referring to this variability as "pluralism," and that term seems to have caught on. "Variability" and "pluralism" are thus used to mean more or less the same thing.
